snippet.textDisplay: A fart is composed of mostly intestinal gas or in this case endogenous, this gas is produced when the bacteria inside your colon breaks down the food you eat. Endogenous gas is mainly composed of hydrogen, carbon dioxide, and occasionally methane with small amounts of other gases included. One more noteworthy gas in a fart is hydrogen sulfide which is what makes the fart smell bad. Hydrogen, which is nearly 30 times lighter than the air we breath, can compose nearly 50% of a fart. As I stated earlier a fart consists of carbon dioxide as well as occasionally methane. Carbon dioxide being 1.5 times heavier than air and methane being lighter than air, your average fart contains nearly 75% lighter than air ingredients. This means you would have to fart a lot to make a difference to your weight, if you were using a scale that reads into the thousandths of a pound a fart would be noticeable in your overall weight.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hypothesis: I believe that whether you gain or lose weight when you fart is a matter of how dense the gas is that is produced by the flatulence vs the density of the fluid surrounding the person who passed the gas.
Given: Weight is a function of (Mass x Acceleration of gravity) - the buoyant force. [W = ma - b]
Assumption: Our body's volume changes is directly proportional to the volume of the fart; therefore we can use a balloon on a scale to represent our flatulent person.
Case 1: Flatulent is more dense than the surrounding fluid. In this case when we release the flatulence from the balloon it is more dense than the surrounding fluid, thus decreasing our 'ma' term more than we decrease the 'b' term. this leads to us loosing weight. [think letting sulfur hexafluoride out of the balloon, the balloon on the scale will get lighter]
Case 2: Flatulent is the same density as the surrounding fluid. In this case when we release the flatulence, since both are the same density the 'ma' and 'b' terms will decrease proportionally to each other. This means that the weight on the scale will not change. [think letting the normal air out of the balloon]
Case 3: Flatulent is less dense than the surrounding fluid. In this case when we release the flatulence from the balloon it is less dense than the surrounding fluid, thus decreasing our 'b' term more than we decrease the 'ma' term. this leads to us gaining weight. [think letting helium out of the balloon, the balloon on the scale will get heavier]

snippet.textDisplay: You lose weight when you fart. Farts are lighter than air, but the whole reason you (usually) fart is due to a high amount of this gas occupying a more or less fixed volume container. Thus, when you fart, you expel enough gas that it offsets the possible weight gain of your colon getting filled by regular air (which is usually not the case). That is, of course, assuming that farts aren't radically lighter than air, in which case "ingesting" regular air again could in fact make you heavier.

snippet.textDisplay:
Fart is mostly made out of methane that is 'lighter' than air (actually not lighter, it's just less dense than air, like helium). It makes people think methane/helium actually pulls you up and makes you also lighter, thus reducing your weight. So when you let the gas out, your body becomes heavier again (like how a balloon falls if you let all the helium out).

But what is 'weight'? Weight is the product of mass times gravity. We see that air and buoyancy has no role in determining an object's weight. Everything has its own mass, including our fart. So naturally, fart has its own weight too. We can hypothetically test this by measuring a helium/fart filled balloon's weight inside a vacuum chamber, and compare it to a collapsed one.

So my answer is you will be lighter (absolute weight reduction happens) when you fart, as you let some weight off from your body. But this change of weight is so small that I guess it can't be measured by our regular body scale.
